      <hedline>
        <hl1>On the Grand Day for Bush, American Voices</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John Yinger letter says Republicans projected a diverse image at national convention (Aug 1 article) but would condemn companies, universities or government agencies that practice same kind of affirmative action</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To increase the diversity of the presentations, the organizers of the Republican National Convention selected some speakers largely on the basis of their sex or skin color (front page, Aug. 1). When a university or a company or a government agency does this, Republican leaders call it affirmative action and condemn it.  How paradoxical it would be if this hypocrisy won them the election.</p>
        <p>JOHN YINGER  Fayetteville, N.Y., Aug. 1, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of economics and public administration, Syracuse University.</p>
      </block>
